Thought process
Here's the concrete path to get this fully live, in order:

1. Register your TikTok app. Go to developers.tiktok.com, sign up, and register an app (Manage apps → Connect an app).

2. Add the Content Posting API product to the app, and under Login Kit register the redirect URI http://127.0.0.1:8722/callback/ (or the wildcard form http://127.0.0.1:*/callback/).

3. Copy your Client key and Client secret into credentials/.env:

TIKTOK_CLIENT_KEY=...
TIKTOK_CLIENT_SECRET=...
4. Request the video.publish scope and submit for review. This is the step that actually matters for hands-off posting — you'll need a privacy policy URL and a demo video showing the full login + post flow. This is also where you decide: submit for the full audit (unlocks real public posting) or skip it and only ever get private/self-only posts. Given you want hands-off, go for the audit. Expect roughly 1–6 weeks.

5. While waiting, do a dry run of the login flow. Once your app shows as connected (even pre-approval, the OAuth login itself should work), run:

python cli.py tiktok-auth
This confirms the redirect URI and PKCE flow are wired correctly before you're relying on it for real. Posting calls will likely still fail with a scope/permission error until the review completes — that's expected.

6. Once approved, test one clip manually before trusting the automation with it:

python cli.py tiktok-upload path/to/clip.mp4 --mode direct --title "test caption #test"
Check what privacy_level comes back — if it's SELF_ONLY instead of PUBLIC_TO_EVERYONE, the audit hasn't fully cleared yet (or your account itself is private).

7. Flip the switches in config/config.yaml:

yaml
tiktok:
  enabled: true
  auto_send_after_youtube: true
  mode: "direct"
Same checkbox is available in the Streamlit sidebar if you'd rather toggle it there per-session.

8. Run a normal automation pass (python cli.py auto-daily, or a manual clip through the app) and confirm both a YouTube and a TikTok post land with matching titles/hashtags.

Everything past step 4 is already built and tested — steps 1–4 are the only parts that require you to act in TikTok's dashboard, and I can't do those for you since they need your own account/business details. Let me know once you've got the client key/secret and I'll help debug the first real login.

